The passage you quoted is from the Chinese classic **《孟子》** (Mencius), specifically from the chapter **《公孫丑上》** (Gongsun Chou I).  

The full paragraph (as it appears in the standard text) is:

> 「敢問何謂浩然之氣？」  
> 曰：「難言也。其為氣也，至大至剛，以直養而無害，則塞乎天地之間；其為氣也，配義與道，無是則餒；夫義，內省而不肯為者，非也；外合而非其內者，非也；財賄之於我，如淝水之投石也；聲色之於我，如溫風之吹毫也；位卑而不足以榮賢者，非也；位高而不足以貪富者，非也；富貴不能淫，貧賤不能移，威武不能屈。此之謂浩然之氣。」

In English (a common translation):

> “May I ask what is meant by the ‘vast and flowing qi’?”  
> He replied: “It is difficult to put into words. This qi is supremely great and unyielding; if one nourishes it with uprightness and does no harm, it will fill the space between heaven and earth. This qi matches righteousness and the Way; without them it starves. For righteousness, if one inwardly knows what is right yet refuses to act, that is not it; if one outwardly conforms but lacks inner sincerity, that is not it. Wealth and honor to me are like a stone thrown into the Yi River; pomp and circumstance are like a warm breeze blowing on a feather. Low position that does not suffice to honor the worthy is not it; high position that does not suffice to tempt greed is not it. Wealth and honor cannot corrupt, poverty and lowliness cannot sway, might and force cannot subdue. This is what is meant by the ‘vast and flowing qi’.”

So the excerpt you provided is the opening of Mencius’s discussion of the “浩然之氣” (the “vast and flowing qi” or “noble spirit”) in **《孟子·公孫丑上》**. [end of text]


